===Etymology===
From Early Modern English {{m|en|pleasur}}, {{m|en|plesur}}, alteration (with ending accommodated to {{m|en|-ure}}) of {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|plaisir||pleasure}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|plesir}}, {{m|fro|plaisir||to please}}, infinitive used as a noun, conjugated form of {{m|fro|plaisir}} or {{m|fro|plaire}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|placeo|placēre|to please, to seem good}}, from the {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*plā-k-||wide and flat}}. Related to {{cog|nl|plezier||pleasure, fun}}. More at {{l|en|please}}.

